'''''D<U+00E9>sert''''' is the title of a novel written by French author and [[Nobel Prize in Literature|Nobel laureate]] [[J. M. G. Le Cl<U+00E9>zio]], considered to be one of his breakthrough novels.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/people/l/jeanmarie_gustave_le_clezio/index.html?inline=nyt-per |title= Jean-Marie Gustave Le Cl<U+00E9>zio|accessdate=2009-01-15 |work= |publisher= The New York Times |date= 2009-01-15 | first=Sarah | last=Lyall}}</ref> It won the [[Acad<U+00E9>mie fran<U+00E7>aise]]'s Grand Prix Paul Morand in 1980.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/the_tls/article709674.ece |title=A Frenchman and a geographer |accessdate=9 December 2008 |work= 5th paragraph|publisher=review is taken from the TLS |date=  April 21, 2006|quote="Le Clezio received the Acad<U+00E9>mie fran<U+00E7>aise's Grand Prix Paul Morand in 1980 for Desert, a novel that revealed a move towards a more expansive and lyrical style" | location=London | first=Adrian | last=Tahourdin}}</ref>

==Plot summary==
Two stories are interwoven. The shorter, which begins and ends the book, is specifically set in 1910<U+2013>1912 and tells of the last uprising of the desert tribes against the [[French protectorate of Morocco]], mostly as observed by a small boy, Nour. The longer, the story of Lalla, is set in an indefinite time, but obviously after the Second World War.  It describes her early life in a  [[Shanty town|Shanty "city"]] on the edge of an unnamed [[Morocco|Moroccan]] coastal town, and particularly her friendship with [[Haratin|"the Hartani"]] who, like her, originates from the desert tribes. It narrates the time she spends in [[Marseilles]] and her eventual return to the shanty city, where she gives birth to the Hartani's child.

