;Review taken from ''Deseret News'' (Salt Lake City)
{{Quotation|Le Clezio made his breakthrough as a novelist with "Desert", in 1980, a work the academy said "contains magnificent images of a lost culture in the North African desert contrasted with a depiction of Europe seen through the eyes of unwanted immigrants."<ref name= Nobel>{{Cite web |url=http://nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/literature/laureates/2008/bio-bibl.html |title=Biobibliographical Notes on Jean-Marie Gustave Le Cl<U+00E9>zio|accessdate=2 January 2009 |work=Bio-bibliography|publisher= The Swedish Academy who awarded The Nobel Prize in Literature 2008|year=2008|quote=His definitive breakthrough as a novelist came with D<U+00E9>sert (1980), for which he received a prize from the French Academy. This work contains magnificent images of a lost culture in the North African desert, contrasted with a depiction of Europe seen through the eyes of unwanted immigrants. The main character, the Algerian guest worker Lalla, is a utopian antithesis to the ugliness and brutality of European society.}}</ref>

That novel, which also won Le Clezio a prize from the French Academy, is considered a masterpiece. It describes the ordeal of Lalla, a woman from the [[Taureg people|Tuareg]] nomadic tribe of the Sahara Desert, as she adapts to civilization imposed by colonial France|Matt Moore<ref>{{cite news
| url         = http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4188/is_/ai_n30903952
